        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Crowhurst Park | Battle— Sussex</placeName>
                    <date>Aug<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. 4.—</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>At this place,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I find many of this charming Epipactis—very erect &amp; showy—&amp; the leaves <hi rend="underline">beautiful</hi>—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Sincerely | G. C. Oxenden—</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is conjectured from Oxenden’s reference to <hi rend="italic">Epipactis</hi> (see n. 3, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Crowhurst Park, Sussex, was the estate of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3665.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Thomas Papillon</ref>, the husband of Oxenden’s sister, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3664.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Frances Margaret Papillon</ref> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1095.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Burke’s landed gentry</hi></ref> 1862).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">In letters written earlier in the summer of 1862, Oxenden discussed various species of <hi rend="italic">Epipactis</hi>, and promised to send CD specimens later in the season (see letters from G. C. Oxenden, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-3553.xml" resp="#automat">15 May 1862</ref>, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-3589.xml" resp="#automat">4 June [1862]</ref>, and [before 21 June 1862]); Oxenden sent specimens of <hi rend="italic">E. palustris</hi> with his letter of 8 July 1862. See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-3728.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from G. C. Oxenden, 17 September [1862]</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
